November 14th, 1847:

Made camp on King William Island, it shall shelter us for the winter.

January 3rd, 1848:

Met a group of Inuit to the Northwest. They were reluctant at first, but later approached us to trade for iron. They offered us dead seals, which o.c. we civilly declined having enough fine canned food aboard Styx and Hades to last a lifetime but instead they may know of a route to NW passage.

March 11th, 1848:

The Inuit led us to a channel heading deeper into the ice. Inuit look worried, but our instruments report freeze is thinning by the day time for our mighty icebreakers to prove their prowess! Soon we shall be the first to cut the miracle shipping canal bridging East and West! We set out tomorrow.

children.name: Text
children.value:
April 26th, 1848:

We have been forced to abandon HMS Styx and HMS Hades. Waited entire summer for the thaw, but weather gods are against us, and they are still stuck fast in the ice. I am certain we can still find NW passage by foot, walking inland.
Have filled two lifeboats with essential supplies to pull them over the snow like sleds. When we next find water it will be a passage to the east! And the lifeboats can row us to a safe haven.

May 4th, 1848:

The men tire. Dragging two lifeboats perhaps ambitious, and they were stopping to rest at regular intervals.
I have ordered that all remaining supplies be trusted to one of the lifeboats from now on, but now we have double the pulling power.
Despite setbacks, morale is pretty good, and we haven't lost any men since winter on Baffling island.

children.name: Text
children.value:
May 11th, 1848:

We are at a crossroads. To determine the best way forward, I sent a team led by Cdr. H. Sturgeon through the canyon to the North. A second team led by Lt Cdr. R. Des Yeux went over the snow dunes to the West. The last team led by Lt Cdr. E. Couch went towards deep chasms in the East.

May 14th, 1848:

No team has yet returned. Camp supplies are becoming rather scarce, and there's little out here to hunt. I think we'd even gobble up those seals the Inuit offered us now.

May 16th, 1848:

Only two of the three teams have returned. I fear the worst has befallen Edgar Couch's men a risk we all took the day we volunteered. It's hard out here, cruel. The rest of us are to move without delay; their sacrifice will not be wasted if we make it.
Cdr. Sturgeon reports that his canyon tapered to a dead end. Des Yeux, God thank him, reports something more promising. We will take the path he took. The ground looks too weak for the boat, but I'm sure we'll think of something, we always do.

children.name: Text
children.value:
June 21st, 1848

Perhaps the warnings of these Inuit had worth. The ice desert has been treacherous, and we have lost both men and equipment. I see darkness in the eyes of the living, now that their companions lie buried. If you knew that we are also at the end of our supplies, you might understand their anger.
But they are loyal men, and know they cannot hope to survive alone. They will only challenge me if I admit defeat, and that I refuse.

A sheer mountain lies ahead. I have had to stifle my shock at its sudden appearance, and at the perilous climb we must now undertake, for morale among the men is already low. I would not appear in my right mind as their leader if I asked them to turn and face the horrors of the desert we had all thought behind us. No. We climb. And meeting us at the summit, I believe, will be a view upon the shimmering water of a Northwest passage that shall sate the hunger.

children.name: Text
children.value:
June 30th, 1848:

Lost my best man, Cdr. Sturgeon, in the mountains. Poor man was too anxious to prove me right. Some made it, but all hungry and desperate. You need shovel-loads to fuel your belly up here, and we have no food at all. There were grunts and growls in the night. Either we eat the resident bears or they eat us.

children.name: Text
children.value:
August 3rd, 1848:

Sir John has entrusted me, Lt. Cdr. Remi Des Yeux, with the completion of his log, as he no longer has the strength to put pen to paper. Still, there can't be many more entries left for me to write.

We are no longer killed by bears, but have been lost days and weeks in high valleys that all look the same having lost our compass. We are now only six: Captain John Faithful; Sargent, the first mate; Little, an engineer; Hodgson, an assistant surgeon, Irving a ship's boy, and myself. The boy lives because he is a good lad, and none could suffer to eat of him. The bear meat never was going to last, you see. Sir John did have us swear never to speak of that shame, but who does he think we will tell?

children.name: Text
children.value:
August 7th, 1848:

Sir John speaks again. He says the silhouette of a great wolf came to him in his sleep, and that he wishes to meet us.

Our pack is down to three. Sir John, the boy Irving and me, Remi Des Yeux. We shall remember Sargent, Little and Hodgson. We shall remember the others who tripped and fell, who froze, who fell ill, who starved, who drowned, were maimed by bears, who slipped on high, or fell through the cracks. And we remember those who, when we ran out of food, drew the short straw...in vain!

If a passage exists, we did not find it. But though he is mad, I will accompany Sir John to the end. The ferocious ship's boy Irving is our guardian spirit, the same who with superhuman strength, was able to fend off grown men in the snow who were after his legs for supper.

children.name: Text
children.value: The explorers are understandably fed up with pemmican. Although bread wouldn't last a day in the Arctic, tunnbrd  a tipical Northern flatbread  would be easy enough to cook on the fire and alleviate their craving, but it requires flour.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ah, I miss bread... Pemmican is convenient, but... I know, we could make some tunnbrd! I've read about it, it should be easy enough to cook, if we had flour...

children.name: Text
children.value: The Arctic is dangerous enough without having to worry about slipping in a puddle of melted snow at every step. The explorer has asked you for felt, to line their soles and keep their feet in place.

children.name: Text
children.value: I learned my fair share of tricks back when I traversed the pampas. Fishermen lined the soles of their boots with felt to prevent slipping. We could use anything that helps us stay in place!

children.name: Text
children.value: It looks like you may stay in the Arctic for quite some time. In that case, the explorer has an idea to better insulate the floor of the camp from the cold: laying on a thick layer of cement between it and the frozen ground.

children.name: Text
children.value: Will our mission in the Arctic extend much longer...? If so, we might want to look into improving the thermal insulation of our tents. Cement is cold, but the frozen ground is colder...!

children.name: Text
children.value: The explorer has asked you to bring saltpetre. It looks like she has something in mind.

children.name: Text
children.value: I have an idea! Could you have a ship bring saltpetre?

children.name: Text
children.value: Yes! Now we only have to spread it on our roads to keep them free of snow! Wait, what do you mean saltpetre is not the same thing as salt? Oh...

children.name: Text
children.value: The explorer's dear little brother is turning eleven! She has never once missed the celebration before, so she has asked you to take a picture of her family, to help her cope with the homesickness.

children.name: Text
children.value: My family will be celebrating little brother's birthday. If only I had a tiny window to feel I'm there at the pub with them... You could bring me a picture?

children.name: Text
children.value: The explorer's family is celebrating at a pub in the Old World.

children.name: Text
children.value: From endless dreamlike landscapes to mighty predators  the explorer is fascinated by the Arctic. She has asked you to take a picture of one of its wonders, so she can keep the memory close to her heart once the adventure is over.

children.name: Text
children.value: Harp seal pups are one of the most endearing creatures I've ever come across. Granted, they don't exude the most pleasant of smells, but you can't smell a photograph, can you?

children.name: Text
children.value: There is a colony of seals at the vast northern ice cap, you will need an airship to find them.

children.name: Text
children.value: I wouldn't want to remember whales for the long hours elbow-deep into their blubber, but swimming free  gargantuan yet majestic  breaching off the icy ocean...

children.name: Text
children.value: Whales can be spotted swimming all across the region.

children.name: Text
children.value: Polar bears hold an enormous significance to the Inuit people. Not only are they essential for their subsistence, they honour them as if they were human  nay, gods. Could you to capture one for me? I-in a picture, of course!

children.name: Text
children.value: There is a bear cave at the vast northern ice cap, you will need an airship to find it.

children.name: Text
children.value: Icebergs are born when ice shelves break apart. A dazzling giant of ice floating away  that's a sight I would love to keep with me for the rest of my days!

children.name: Text
children.value: There is an iceberg slowly floating around the region.

children.name: Text
children.value: The reality of the Arctic is very different from what the explorer had dreamt of. Still, she is determined to make her family proud. She has asked you to take a picture of her and her colleagues, and she will do her best to pose with her biggest smile.

children.name: Text
children.value: Mother and father have never been but supportive of my dream of exploring the Arctic. Yes, it is tougher than I anticipated here, but I will not let them worry. They shall only see my beaming smile!

children.name: Text
children.value: Take a picture of the explorer and her colleagues.

children.name: Text
children.value: Narwahls do not possess the magical properties their tusks were attributed in the black market, I know. But I do feel an indescribable awe upon seeing them...

children.name: Text
children.value: Narwhals can be spotted swimming all across the region.

children.name: Text
children.value: One of the passions the explorer has inherited from her father is sketching the fauna during her travels. There are some species she is still missing on her Arctic sketchbook. You can help her find them.

children.name: Text
children.value: My father drew the most beautiful wolves when he hiked through the fjords. I would like to have a sketch of my own, but I have yet to find one...

children.name: Text
children.value: Have you heard the rumours? They say a moose has been spotted near the mines. That would be an incredible addition to my sketchbook...!

children.name: Text
children.value: There is one animal my father could never draw: the great polar bear. It would be the best gift I could ever bring him, if I found a model.

children.value: It is pure arrogance to think we know more about the Arctic than the Inuit. They should be put in charge  of our administrations!

children.name: Text
children.value: If people back home knew half of what I've learned from the Inuit, they would stop acting as if they were better than them! Here, they gifted me this after I stayed with them for a fortnight: display it in a museum, spread their culture.

children.value: The explorer's friend Arno and the rest of his research group went to the vast northern ice cap to track a colony of seals, but they haven't returned and she is getting worried about them.

children.name: Text
children.value: An exploration party is gathering to reach the north pole by sled. I told them you might be able to help. T-they only need you to take them to the ice cap to the north! They will continue from there...

children.name: Text
children.value: Looks like that's exploration party that was trying to reach the north pole in dog sleds has not returned yet. The explorer is getting a little worried about them, and has asked you to go looking for them in the ice.

children.name: Text

children.name: Text
children.value: The great Sir William Perry got further North than no other before him, long before the Styx was even assembled. But his ship, the Angry Wrath, became icebound. He left it behind to save his crew. It's still out here somewhere...

children.name: Text
children.value: The explorer wonders if you would be able to find the remains of the HMS Angry Wrath, the ship Sir William Perry had to abandon in the ice during his expedition to the Arctic, long ago.

children.value: The explorer proposes to look for the remains of failed expeditions.

children.name: Text
children.value: Many have tried their luck at exploring the Arctic  and failed. The explorer has proposed to go soaring the skies in search for remaining parts that could be repurposed by Old Nate.

children.name: Text
children.value: We shared stories on the ship. A gruff man said this was his second time sailing to the Arctic  the first time around his crew had to leave much equipment behind to make it out alive. Do you think it's still out there?

children.name: Text
children.value: The Arctic may seem barren, but it is no junkyard! Every bit of scrap left behind in the ice throws the delicate balance of this environment off! We can  no  we must collect and recicle as much of it as we can find!

children.name: Text
children.value: I always kept an eye out on the newspapers for news on Arctic expeditions. There were very few updates on most of them... Such a loss of resources! We could still honour those brave explorers by not letting their efforts go to waste.

children.name: Text
children.value: The explorer reminds you to take the scrap to Old Nate.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Technicians need pocket watches. In the Arctic it is light all day, and they need accurate reference as to the hour.

children.name: Text
children.value: Confounded Arctic summers! Hard to know what time it is when it's light all day we need pocket watches.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Technician has asked for champagne. Apart from a little home comfort, the bubbles may prove influential in scientific circles.

children.name: Text
children.value: Now there's champagne, Fritz won't hesitate to name me co-author on his magnetism paper. I may even get a mention at some award ceremony.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Technician wants Coal and Steam Carriages to fuel his theory that the Arctic climate can be manipulated. He is hoping you aren't  the type to doubt the experts...

children.name: Text
children.value: I posit that warming the Arctic will have a startling impact on the climate back home! In my latest paper, I want to prove the potential benefits of pumping smog into the Arctic sky!

children.name: Text
children.value: The Technician wants his picture taken alongside his instruments and equipment, just in case his seismic contribution to science isn't given the attention it surely merits.

children.name: Text
children.value: I want my picture taken so that I receive due credit for this earth-shattering discovery. We are now a step closer to understanding how The World came into being, so naturally I deserve to be the centre of attention.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Technician to be photographed is the one who gave you the quest.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Technician wants a picture of a specific crevasse and mountain to show he has conquered it. Sssh! Don't tell anyone that you took it from an airship, and he never bothered to make the ascent.

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm no mere hobbyist, I want a proper photograph of the landform I conquered. Seeing the high glacier, observers will realise just what I am willing to endure for authentic research.

children.name: Text

children.value: The Technician wants wild Arctic animal subjects for dissection, such as Wolves or Elk.

children.name: Text
children.value: We should dissect and scrutinise every furry beastie we can snare. It's a great opportunity to get at them before people start whipping out the red tape.

children.name: Text
children.value: Wild animals can be found on your island close to the mines.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Technician wants to see glacial serac up close for his privately-funded research project.

children.name: Text
children.value: If I tried to explain the formation of glacial serac, you probably wouldn't have the foggiest notion. Well to simplify, serac are pillars of ice formed of the glacier.

children.name: Text
children.value: Click the jump-to button to discover the location of the serac. You'll need to clear the fog around it with your airship.

children.name: Text
children.value: A group of Technicians want to set up a research station in the remote North. If you drop them up there, they should come back with some interesting new findings given time.

children.name: Text
children.value: We've found something utterly fascinating, and we want you to construct a field station for us. Something up in the far north is sending our instruments haywire!

children.name: Text
children.value: Drop the scientists at the specified point in the far North. Use your jump-to button to locate it.

children.name: Text
children.value: You dropped a team of researchers in the far North to set up a research station, but a Technician informs you that nothing has been heard from them in some considerable time. He suggests you go looking for them.

children.name: Text
children.value: We've not heard a peep from the field station in ages, I do hope nothing is amiss. But if something is amiss...perhaps that's the very THING we are looking for...

children.name: Text
children.value: The Technician found a note that may point to the site of the research station.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Technician lampoons you for searching the wrong site.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Technician is dumbfounded by the odd happenings at the research center.

children.name: Text
children.value:
Proposed locations for our research station:
Upon an offshore ice platform South of here. Pros: Isolated. Cons: Melty.
At the foot of a tall mountain which ends in the sea, West of here. Pros: The mountain shields us from storms. Cons: Signs of human activity we may be disturbed by locals.
At the end of a crevasse to the North. Pros: I can throw Musgrave in the sealhole if he interferes with my researches again. Cons: Musgrave might have the same idea.

children.name: Text
children.value: Go back to the location where you carried the researchers. Use the jump-to button to locate it.

children.name: Text
children.value: Pick up the journal in the cairn and read it to find the research center.

children.name: Text
children.value:
Have a once-Pyrphorian flamethrower at close hand to light up that thing if it should return! I spent the afternoon hosing Musgrave's superior collection of cacti with flame. I don't suppose he'll mind now, Musgrave, but he failed my little test. How was I to know if it was the real him?
I hear barking outside, yet all the huskies were dead! Aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaah!

children.name: Text
children.value: A Technician explains that mammoth would have roamed free all over the northern hemisphere during the Ice Age. He is excited by the prospect that some might be found suspended in ice to the northwest.

children.name: Text
children.value: I'm on the trail of the woolly mammoth. I have a hunch some may still be in trapped in the ice to the northwest.

children.name: Text
children.value: Find the mammoth trapped in the ice by following mammoth bones in the far north. The trail begins where the Technician has indicated.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Technician has found mammoth bones leading off somewhere.

children.name: Text
children.value: The scientist is thrilled to find a perfectly-preserved Mammoth.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Technician is amazed by the prehistoric human you found in the ice.

children.name: Text
children.value: Find the prehistoric man trapped in the ice and bring him back to your Trading Post.

children.name: Text
children.value: A Technician is bursting with excitement to have seen what he believes to be a human trapped in ice from your airship. He thinks you ought to take it back to your Trading Post for a more thorough examination.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq has asked you for whale oil to fuel the "Kudliks" lamps to light the dark of endless night.

children.name: Text
children.value: We need more blubber for the kudliks. Their fire will lift the darkness.

children.name: Text
children.value: The rite of passage for many young Inuit is a test of their hunting skills. Normally it would be seal or a caribou, but Qumaq's son Aput, being a late developer, has been tasked with hunting a bear.

children.name: Text
children.value: A boy who provides is a man, and my boy has yet to provide. Can you find out how Aput's hunt progresses?

children.name: Text
children.value: Seal or caribou would be easy for me, but a bear? I see Nanuk, and the soul of grandpa "Grey Bear" before me. I can't do it. Please, help me!

children.name: Text
children.value: Thanks. I should feel guilty, but I don't. What adult sends a kid to catch a bear? I never want to grow up.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq has asked you to help him catch some seals.

children.name: Text
children.value: Hear the ice cracking? Time to hunt seal, it is easier in the spring.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq has entrusted you with delivering his community some goose feathers. Geese are animals, like others, that seem to have a great many uses for the Inuit.

children.name: Text
children.value: Want to help us catch goose? A few more feathers for our pillows would be nice. I hope you use the rest of the bird too...

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq's experienced huskies Ernouk and Tortu died in a dog-sled accident. Having decided to get back in the saddle, he hopes you can repair his sled, and find him new dogs.

children.name: Text
children.value: I loved those dogs...the accident cost Ernouk and Tortu their lives, and my best sled is still broken.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq would like to shear some New World Alpacas for Parkas, to see if they are an improvement upon seal and caribou lining.

children.name: Text
children.value: Alpaca wool is warm you say? Warmer than our Parkas? Prove it!

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq has asked you to deliver sails for his old umiak. He hopes they will be an improvement on the rotting oars.

children.name: Text
children.value: Can sails have value here? My umiak has seen better days, maybe these sails will help.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq is willing to take some pigs from you, to see if they are able to survive in the Arctic circle.

children.name: Text
children.value: You think we should keep pigs? Okay. Send us your pigs.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq is willing to take some Fish Oil from you, to see if it suits the purposes of the Inuit.

children.name: Text
children.value: Fish Oil you say? We need oil for a lot of things. Let's see if it's tasty too.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq has asked you to deliver some glasses to see if they might be useful to his community.

children.name: Text
children.value: Do you mean snow goggles, or something else? Show me these glasses of yours.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq is open to you delivering coffee for his community, in case it helps with the long Inuit workday.

children.name: Text
children.value: A black drink called coffin? If you think it will keep us alert, I suppose we can give it a try.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq asks you to find some Inuit children and send them home.

children.name: Text
children.value: Some children snuck off to see your city, please can you send them home? Whatever made them leave, we can talk about it.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq has entrusted you to make a photo of the mystic clouds.

children.name: Text
children.value: One of the trader has discovered some mystic clouds, colouring the northern lake. He's too afraid to take his way home. Please make a photo.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq asks for a photo of a natural formation exactly like the one in their camp, lost somewhere in the vast northern ice cap.

children.name: Text
children.value: See the natural formation near camp. Our elders tell stories of it being one of two twins. Do you know of any other like it?

children.name: Text
children.value: The natural formation is at the vast northern ice cap, you will need an airship to find it.

children.name: Text
children.value:
Find and Photograph:
[AssetData([Conditions QuestCondition Context]) Text]

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq asks you to photograph an anomaly on the Southern coast.

children.name: Text
children.value: One of our people saw something terrible washed up on a beach. Can you bring me a picture?

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq asks you to dive using your diving bell in order to look for a troublesome sea monster that has claimed some of his community.

children.name: Text
children.value: If I could see down to the depths, I would find the monster that has claimed so many of our fishermen.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq is glad the monster appears to have been banished.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq thinks it safest to retreat.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq asks if you could recover a beloved amulet from the deep.

children.name: Text
children.value: Can your machine find my amulet? I lost it to the sea in a storm. As I tossed and turned in the waves, my special amulet came loose...

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq asks you to rescue the missing crew and their boats.

children.name: Text
children.value: A great wave took many hunters. Higher than a mountain. We are still missing some hunters and their umiaks.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq has asked you to monitor the progress of a group of young hunters who have disappeared up in the north.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ah, daring youth! The young hunters search for seals began in the north.

children.name: Text
children.value: Find the young hunters up north

children.name: Text
children.value: Follow the young hunters through the ice desert

children.name: Text
children.value: Zoom in to scan the terrain and look for tracks.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq has asked you to give three lamps life. A thick fog has fallen the essence of a female giant. If all braziers burning at the same time, the fog should lift and make better conditions for sledding.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Giant drank so much water she burst open, and fog was born. Give the lamps life. Fire the old braziers in the ice and today's fog will lift for sledding.

children.name: Text
children.value: Light the brazier in the North-West

children.name: Text
children.value: Light the brazier in the North

children.name: Text
children.value: Light the brazier in the North-East

children.name: Text
children.value: The fog is lifted. Thank you. We can go sledding now.

children.name: Text
children.value: The braziers are located in the far north.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq wants you to track down a thief, for the thief's own safety as much as anything else.

children.name: Text
children.value: He who stole ran into the mountains. I am worried for him. He has taken one of our best Umiaks and many of our most precious things.

children.name: Text
children.value: This is his first crime, we will talk to him and make him feel loved. Good hunting!

children.name: Text
children.value: Zoom in to scan the terrain and look for tracks.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Inuit has asked you to track down a missing elder who went to find some cranberries that grow on the far side of the mountain. Many Inuit are quite ill with sore throats, and they need those berries.

children.name: Text
children.value: Everyone has bad sore throats. The elder went over the mountain for cranberries, but he hasn't returned. I am worried for him.

children.name: Text
children.value: Fuel a fire to warm the sick and mourn the elder

children.name: Text
children.value: Zoom in to scan the terrain and look for tracks.

children.name: Text
children.value: Follow the trail and find the next clue

children.name: Text
children.value: Fly to the first position indicated by the resident

children.name: Text
children.value: Find the research center to learn what happened

children.name: Text
children.value: Pick up and read the note to guess where they built the research center

children.name: Text
children.value: Pick up the lost cargo: [Conditions QuestCondition CurrentAmount]/[Conditions QuestCondition Amount]

children.name: Text
children.value: These Prime Hunting Cabins gather fur four times faster than the ones in the Old World!

children.name: Text
children.value: Deep Gold Mines here in the Arctic yield more than twice as much gold as the regular ones, hehe...

children.name: Text
children.value: Gas can be drilled in the Arctic, and you can burn it for electricity and all. Try me gas-fired power plants! You don't even need trains to get it working!

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate says goodbye and will be back later.

children.value: [AssetData([NotificationContext CharacterGUID]) Text] offers you an exploration quest.

children.value: [AssetData([NotificationContext CharacterGUID]) Text] offers you an exploration quest.

children.name: Text
children.value: Qumaq rewards you for the kind thought.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ovibos moschatus. Musk ox males emit a strong odor during the seasonal rut, hence the name.

children.name: Text
children.value: Rangifer tarandus. The largest of the caribou, this forest-dwelling species is extremely sensitive to human disturbance of their habitat.

children.name: Text
children.value: Vulpes lagopus. Its snow-white fur keeps it warm and nearly undetectable to the untrained eye.

children.name: Text
children.value: Odobenus rosmarus. Its vibrissae the stiff bristles around its tusks give the walrus a whiskered appearance.

children.name: Text
children.value: Pusa hispida. This small, earless seal is one of the pillars of life in the Arctic known as nattiq by the Inuit.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ursus maritimus. Nanuk. A hypercarnivore adapted to the Arctic who navigates sea ice in search of seals.

children.name: Text
children.value: Pagophila eburnea. This small polar gull has many vocalizations, including a warbling fox-call to warn about predators.

children.name: Text
children.value: Canis lupus arctos. Born an ashy grey, its coat turns white as it matures.

children.name: Text
children.value: Monodon monoceros. The imposing spiral tusks that protrude from their jaws have been harvested and sold as unicorn horns since ancient times.

children.name: Text
children.value: Pinguinus impennis. A very rare bird these days, perhaps because their eggs are so highly prized. Aukward.

children.name: Text
children.value: This small pre-Thule carving was recovered in exceedingly good condition.

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff relics of the expedition

children.name: Text
children.value: A collection of odds and ends from Sir John's Lost Expedition that the Inuit rescued from the ice.

children.name: Text
children.value: Oftentimes confused with the simpler inuksuks, this stone structure resembles a human with wide open arms.

children.name: Text
children.value: This pyramidal inuksuk was built to mark a cache of caribou meat that had been stored for the winter.

children.name: Text
children.value: A miniature children's version of the traditional Inuit sled, complete with gruff husky.

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff Relics of the Expedition

children.name: Text
children.value: An assortment of seemingly worthless miscellaneous items that belonged to the crew of the Lost Expedition.

children.name: Text
children.value: A meticulous replica of the real HMS Hades, which along with the HMS Styx, was wrecked during the Faithful expedition.

children.name: Text
children.value: Traditional Inuit dwellings built with blocks of ice acting as insulation, trapping the body heat of the people within.

children.name: Text
children.value: A well-dressed Inuit mummy over 400 years old. Freeze dried, she looks as if she could have died yesterday.

children.name: Text
children.value: This frozen wolf pup is 50,000 years old, predating the emergence of the domestic dog by at least 10,000 years!

children.name: Text
children.value: A paleontologist's dream. A bit mangled after thousands of years in ice, but still partially furred and fleshed!

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff Ancient Trade Route Map (Arctic)

children.name: Text
children.value: This map leads to an old Inuit settlement.

children.name: Text
children.value: One of the many Huddlesome Bay Company trading posts in the Arctic, mysteriously closed...

children.name: Text
children.value: Land of giants beyond the North Wind  where the sun never sets. Could it really be...?

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff Rare Fishes Distribution Map (Arctic)

children.name: Text
children.value: Seals don't seem to have a problem finding prey in this spot.

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff Threatened Animals Sanctuary Map (Arctic)

children.name: Text
children.value: Hard to believe how much widlife thrives in the depths of the frozen ocean.

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff Mythological Animal Hideout Map (Arctic)

children.name: Text
children.value: Expeditioners exchange stories of the prehistoric giant shark, still frozen in time at the bottom of the deepest, darkest trench of the Arctic.

children.name: Text
children.value: Long ago, this peaceful people too engaged in tribal conflicts.

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff Merchant Ships Sinking Spots Map (Arctic)

children.name: Text
children.value: A young whaler swears they boarded the three-masted vessel and saw her frozen-stiff captain still sitting at his desk, pen-in-hand.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate's first attempts at touching the sky melted his wings prematurely. Prototype X plunged into the depths of the ocean after making some very peculiar screeching sounds

children.name: Text
children.value: Sneak up on poor snoozing whales.

children.name: Text
children.value: Perfect for navigating narrow channels where whales come ashore to sleep at night.

children.name: Text
children.value: So smooth in the water the bowhead cannot hear you as you approach its shoreline bed. Poor whales.

children.name: Text
children.value: An effective Inuit Harpoon when sealing, says Qumaq.

children.name: Text
children.value: The most effective tool for skinning seal, incorporating thousands of years of Inuit knowledge and practice.

children.name: Text
children.value: Soft and silent the arrow buries itself.

children.name: Text
children.value: The arrow flies higher and higher, further and further.

children.name: Text
children.value: This mighty bow of the northwest is powerful enough to bring down a fully-grown moose.

children.name: Text
children.value: A safety precaution to kill bacteria before curing.

children.name: Text
children.value: A safety precaution to kill bacteria before curing. Improved temperature control.

children.name: Text
children.value: Reaches exact temperature prior to the curing process to kill bacteria, but preserve moisture in the meat.

children.name: Text
children.value: Skins must first be treated or clothes made from them will stiffen and rot.

children.name: Text
children.value: Awls make holes for needles to pass through to save them from breaking.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Inuit store needles in these carry cases so that they don't blunt and are always close at hand.

children.name: Text
children.value: Snow goggles that are both comfortable and durable.

children.name: Text
children.value: For those who spend a lot of time out in the snow with the critters, and wish to feel at one with them.

children.name: Text
children.value: A decent tool for shaping wood for Arctic conditions.

children.name: Text
children.value: Useful for smoothing wood surfaces for Arctic conditions.

children.name: Text
children.value: Useful for smoothing wood surfaces for Arctic conditions, and extremely comfortable in the hand.

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff machine quest rewRD pulley

children.name: Text
children.value: Trade faster with this splendiferous pulley which encourages everyone to hurry up and get it done!

children.name: Text
children.value: An average Inuit seamster is likely the best seamster you've ever met.

children.name: Text
children.value: Knows all the patterns perfectly and doesn't waste a scrap of the animal's skin.

children.name: Text
children.value: Once the incomparable Arnarunn has knitted a glowing sleeping bag, it will never need replacing.

children.name: Text
children.value: The dogs and geese won't bite him any more.

children.name: Text
children.value: The geese and the dogs know him as their father.

children.name: Text
children.value: She knows that strong dogs make the best companions, and strong geese have the best feathers.

children.name: Text
children.value: She knows all the best spots, and breathes more quietly than an Arctic Hare.

children.name: Text
children.value: Toklo respects his prey, taking only what he needs. Collects feathers from bird roosts.

children.name: Text
children.value: Learned the craft from his father's father, who learned from his father before that.

children.name: Text
children.value: When trees are few and far between, you learn the places driftwood prefers to end its voyages.

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff Arctic Kitchen Expert Uncommon

children.name: Text
children.value: Has made pemmican many times before.

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff Arctic Kitchen Expert Rare

children.name: Text
children.value: In touch with the origins of Pemmican among the native peoples of the plains.

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff Arctic Kitchen Expert Epic

children.name: Text
children.value: Naturally he is aware Pemmican must be high in fat, but Sandro manages to put some excess to other uses.

children.name: Text
children.value: Irritate coworkers by cranking out the same tunes over and over and over again.

children.name: Text
children.value: Drop a thick walrus steak on the angry red bars, and see the place sizzle up.

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff invention Fat Candle Making Machine

children.name: Text
children.value: With such squat and portly candles stomping off the production line, your lamps can go without brass.

children.name: Text
children.value: Not only current, futuristic! Old N8's futuristic zapper carbonises logs so you don't have to.

children.name: Text
children.value: Spice, booze, a few twists of the handle, and winter no longer seems so cold.

children.name: Text
children.value: The little machine that can. N8 once canned a batch of horse meat with it to sell it in bulk as beef.

children.name: Text
children.value: A crisp and comforting exterior that masks a complex heating system within. Also offers deep storage options.

children.name: Text
children.value: A mule so assiduous in its quest for gas, it is willing to pause only for copper and zinc.

children.name: Text
children.value: Nate didn't have post office employees in mind with this scalding hot coffee conveyor, yet they are lapping it up!

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff invention Kink Spring Powered Motor

children.name: Text
children.value: Old N8 was inspired to rejig his engines after Nordic salmon rained from the sky and beat up his airship.

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff invention Royal Airship Stamp Machine

children.name: Text
children.value: The Royal Airship Service being relatively new meant Old N8 getting his hands on official stamp designs.

children.name: Text
children.value: A chance for employees to absorb all the latest gossip.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate tested the sensors by setting fire to his sleeve.

children.name: Text
children.value: Nate was vexed to find the yak milk butter in his larder had turned a rancid orange and knew something must be done.

children.name: Text
children.value: Flips and replaces shellac records automatically from a collection of popular music hall tunes.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old N8 tired of having to go to an underground cave every time he needed rocks for his whiskey.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old Nate spends his free time playing billiards against a version of himself, commentating every play.

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff invention Fresh Drinks Distributor

children.name: Text
children.value: No time for the pub? Take a selection of sophisticated ales back to work with you in an artisanal carry-box.

children.name: Text
children.value: Old N8 was inspired to create one of these after one of his many trips to the far east.

children.name: Text
children.value: A coffee machine that disgorges the most treacly, eye-opening thimblefuls of hot bean juice.

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff invention Cola Mola Machine

children.name: Text
children.value: Produces a whirligig of soda and vegetable extract that may become a popular alternative to coffee someday.

children.name: Name
children.value: item fluff invention Nitrous Oxide Balloons

children.name: Text
children.value: There are new ways to have fun now we have a better understanding of the noble gases.

children.name: Text
children.value: Doesn't matter what you pile into your cigar, tobacco, hay, dog hair, the weeds around the pumpkins.
